<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-965-518  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 965 518.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Jan 16 1989 v216 n3 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Voice messaging's three ingredients. (Bell regional holdingcompany services)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fermazin, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In Mar 1988 the Bell regional holding companies got permission tooffer voice messaging services but it is not yet known whatcustomers will want or whether customers will respond toaggressive promotions launched by manufacturers and distributorsof customer premises equipment (CPE).andP;  Customers may want theirown systems or they may prefer to patronize service bureaus.andP;  CPEmanufacturers and distributors are profiting from the increasedinterest in voice messaging: Probe Research estimates 1988 salesof CPE at $400 million and sales are expected to exceed $600million in 1989.andP;  What would it take to convince customers tosubscribe to voice messaging provided by service bureaus orcentral offices? Three requirements are cited: features,viability, and customer perception that a service is economical.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Probe Research Inc. (statistics).andO;Topic:     Telephone CompaniesVoice CommunicationsBell Regional Holding CompaniesGovernment RegulationTelephone systemsOutlookMarketing Research.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>